###########################
#  Initialization

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PGgraphmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
  "contextRationalFunction.pl",
 
);

##############################################


Context("RationalFunction");
$var = list_random('x', 'y', 'z', 'a', 'b', 'c', 't', 'm', 'n', 'p');
Context()->variables->are($var =>'Real');

#problem is of the form:
# [(cx + a)(x + b)]/[-(x + b)(x - b)]
$a = non_zero_random(-8, 8);
$b = non_zero_random(1, 7);
$c = random(2, 4);

$last = $a*$b;
$middle = $a + $b*$c;
$bc = $b*$c;
$prod = $c*$last;

$eqn2 = Formula("$var^2 - $b**2")->reduce;

#Question
$g = Formula("($c*$var^2 + ($a + $c*$b)*$var + $a*$b)/($b**2 - $var^2)")->reduce;

#Answer
#The negative is in the numerator
$f = Formula("(-$c*$var - $a)/($var - $b)")->reduce;

#custom checker to make sure it is reduced.  It checks to see that answers are equivalent and then checks to see that the numerators are the same.  Custom checker doesn't enforce polynomial format though... 
$cmp = $f->cmp(checker => sub {
  my ($correct,$student,$ans) = @_;
  return 0 unless $correct == $student;
  return 0 unless $student->{tree}->class eq "BOP" && $student->{tree}{bop} eq "/";
  my $cnum = Formula($correct->{tree}{lop});
  my $snum = Formula($student->{tree}{lop});
Value->Error("Your answer isn't reduced") unless (($cnum == $snum)||($cnum == -$snum));
  return 1;
});


##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Simplify the rational expression.

[``[$g] = ``]  [________]{$cmp}
 
END_PGML

##############################################



BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
We can only cancel common factors, so you must factor before you can simplify.

To factor the numerator, look for two numbers with a product of [`[$c] \cdot [$last] = [$prod]`] and a sum of [`[$middle]`].  Those numbers are [$bc] and [$a].

[`[$c][$var]^2 + [$a][$var] + [$bc][$var] + [$last]`]

[`[$var]([$c][$var] + [$a]) + [$b]([$c][$var] + [$a])`]

[`([$c][$var] + [$a])([$var] + [$b])`]

To factor the denominator, take out a -1.

[`-1([$eqn2])`]

[`-1([$var] + [$b])([$var] - [$b])`]

In factored form, the problem is now:

[`\displaystyle \frac{([$c][$var] + [$a])([$var]+[$b])}{-1([$var] + [$b])([$var] - [$b])}`]

[`([$var] + [$b])`] is a common factor.  If we reduce this we are left with [`\displaystyle [$f]`].
END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();